      <title>量子力学笔记（三）</title>
      <link href="/archives/d22f550e.html"/>
      <url>/archives/d22f550e.html</url>
      
        <content type="html"><![CDATA[<h2 id="Hilbert-Space">Hilbert Space</h2><ul><li><p>The <strong>state</strong> of a system is represented by its wave function,  <strong>observables</strong> are represented by operators</p></li><li><p>Wave functions live in Hilbert space</p><ul><li><p>the set of all <strong>square-integrable</strong> functions</p><ul><li>$\int_a^b|f(x)|^2dx$</li><li>$\int|\Psi|^2dx=1$</li></ul></li><li><p>inner product of two functions</p><ul><li>$\lang f|g\rang \equiv \int_a^b f(x)^*g(x)dx$</li></ul></li></ul></li></ul><h2 id="Observables">Observables</h2><ul><li><p>$\lang Q\rang=\lang\Psi|\hat{Q}\Psi\rang$</p></li><li><p>Hermitian Operator</p><ul><li><p>$\left \langle f|\hat{Q}g\right \rangle=\left \langle \hat{Q}f|g\right \rangle $for all f(x) and all g(x)</p><blockquote><p>the outcome of measurement has got be real</p></blockquote></li><li><p>Observables are represented by hermitian operator</p><ul><li>$\hat{Q}=\hat{Q}^\dagger$</li></ul></li></ul></li><li><p>Determinate States</p><ul><li>Determinate states of $Q$ are eigenfunctions of $\hat{Q}$<ul><li>$\hat{Q}\Psi=q\Psi$</li></ul></li></ul></li></ul><h2 id="Eigenfunctions-Of-A-Hermitian-Operator">Eigenfunctions Of A Hermitian Operator</h2><ul><li><p>Discrete Spectra</p><ul><li><p>Theorem1: Their eigenvalues are real</p></li><li><p>Theorem2: Eigenfunctions belonging to distinct eigenvalues are orthogonal</p><ul><li>for degenerate state, we can use the <strong>Gram-Schmidt orthogonalization proedure</strong> to construct orthogonal eigenfunctions within each degenerate space</li></ul></li><li><p>Axiom: The eigenfunctions of an observable operator are complete</p></li></ul></li><li><p>Continuous Spectra</p><ul><li>基矢间的关系、态函数向基矢投影得到系数</li></ul></li><li><table><thead><tr><th>Discrete Spectra</th><th>Continuous Spectra</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td></td><td></td></tr><tr><td>$&lt;f</td><td>f&gt;=\int_a^b</td></tr><tr><td>$&lt;f_m</td><td>f_n&gt;=\delta_{mn}$</td></tr><tr><td>$f(x)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infin}c_nf_n(x)$</td><td>$f(x)=\int_{-\infin}^{\infin}c§f_p(x)dp$</td></tr><tr><td>$c_n=&lt;f_n</td><td>f&gt;$</td></tr></tbody></table></li></ul><h2 id="Generalized-Statistical-Interpretation">Generalized Statistical Interpretation</h2><ul><li>If you measure an observable $Q(x,p)$ on a particle in the state $\Psi(x,t)$, you are certain to get one of the eigenvalues of the hermitian operator $\hat{Q}(x,-i\hbar d/dx)$<ul><li>If the spectrum of $\hat{Q}$ is discrete, the probability of getting the particular eigenvalues $q_n$ associated with the (orthonormalized) eigenfunctions $f_n(x)$ is<ul><li>$|c_n|^2 $     where    $c_n=\lang f_n|\Psi\rang$</li></ul></li><li>If the spectrum of $\hat{Q}$ is continuous, with real eigenvalues $q(z)$ and associated (Dirac-orthonormalized) eigenfunctions $f_z(x)$, the probability of getting a result in the range $dz$ is<ul><li>$|c(z)|^2dz $      where   $c(z)=\lang f_z|\Psi\rang$</li><li>$\Psi(y,t)=\lang g_y|\Psi\rang$</li><li>$\Phi(p,t)=\lang f_p|\Psi\rang$</li><li>能否根据归一化得出$\int|c(z)|^2dz=1$</li></ul></li></ul></li></ul><h2 id="The-Uncertainty-Principle">The Uncertainty Principle</h2><ul><li><p>$\sigma_A^2\sigma_B^2\ge(\frac{1}{2i}\langle [\hat A, \hat B]\rangle)^2$</p><ul><li>the commutator of two hermitian operators is itself anti-hermitian$(\hat{Q}^\dagger=-\hat{Q})$, and its expectation value is imaginary</li></ul></li><li><p>incompatible observables</p><ul><li><p>observables whose operators do not commute</p></li><li><p>do not have shared eigenfunctions</p></li></ul></li><li><p>The Minimum-Uncertainty Wave Packet</p><ul><li><p>$g(x)=iaf(x)$, where $a$ is real</p><ul><li>不等号成立的条件</li></ul></li><li><p>$(\hat{A}-\langle A\rangle)\Psi=ia(\hat{B}-\langle B\rangle)$</p></li><li><p>Gaussian wave packet</p></li></ul></li><li><p>The Energy-Time Uncertainty Principle</p><ul><li>energy-time uncertainty principle<ul><li>$\Delta t\Delta E\ge\frac{\hbar}{2}$</li><li>$\Delta t=\frac{\sigma_Q}{|d\lang Q\rang/dt|}$</li></ul></li><li>generalized Ehrenfest theorem<ul><li>$\frac{d}{dt}\lang Q\rang=\frac{i}{\hbar}\lang [\hat{iH},\hat{Q}]\rang+\lang \frac{\partial \hat{Q}}{\partial t}\rang$</li><li>$\sigma_H\sigma_Q\ge\frac{\hbar}{2}|\frac{d\lang Q\rang}{dt}|$</li></ul></li></ul></li></ul><h2 id="Vectors-and-Operators">Vectors and Operators</h2><ul><li>Bases in Hilbert Space<ul><li>the wave function is the component in the expansion of $|\mathcal{S}(t)\rang$ in the basis of corresponding eigenfunctions<ul><li>$\Psi(x,t)=\lang x|\mathcal{S}(t)\rang$</li><li>$\Phi(p,t)=\lang p|\mathcal{S}(t)\rang$</li><li>$c_n(t)=\lang n|\mathcal{S}(t)\rang$</li></ul></li><li>linear combination<ul><li>$|\mathcal{S}(t)\rang=\int\Psi(y,t)\delta(x-y)dy=\int\Phi(p,t)\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi\hbar}}e^{ipx/\hbar}dp=\sum c_ne^{-iE_nt/\hbar\psi_n(x)}$</li><li>in position space, $\hat{x}-x$, $|x\rang-\delta(x-y)$, $component-\Psi(x,t)$, $\mathcal{S}(t)-\Psi(x,t)$</li><li>$|\mathcal{S}(t)\rang$大概就是一个抽象的态，在不同空间表示不同</li></ul></li><li>operators (representing observables) are linear transformations on Hilbert space<ul><li>$\lang e_m|\hat{Q}|e_n\rang\equiv Q_{mn}$</li><li>$b_m=\sum_nQ_{mn}a_n$</li></ul></li><li>operators look different when expressed in different bases<ul><li>$\hat{x}=\left{\begin{matrix} x \ i\hbar\partial/\partial p \end{matrix}\right.$</li><li>$\hat{p}=\left{\begin{matrix} -i\hbar\partial/\partial x \ p \end{matrix}\right.$</li></ul></li><li>actually, some systems admit only a finite number $N$ of linearly independent states</li></ul></li><li>Dirac Notation<ul><li>bra and ket<ul><li>$\lang f|=\int f^*[…]dx$</li><li>$\lang\alpha|\to(a_1^<em>a_2^</em>…a_n^*)$</li><li>dual space</li></ul></li><li>operator<ul><li>projection operator<ul><li>$\hat{P}\equiv|\alpha\rang\lang\alpha|$</li><li>idempotent: $\hat{P}^2=\hat{P}$</li></ul></li><li>identity operator (completeness)<ul><li>$\sum_n|e_n\rang\lang e_n|=1$</li><li>$\int|e_z\rang\lang e_z|dz=1$</li></ul></li><li>spectral decomposition<ul><li>$\hat{Q}=\sum_nq_n|e_n\rang\lang e_n|$</li></ul></li><li>functions of operators<ul><li>$f(\hat{Q})=\sum_nf(q_n)|e_n\rang\lang e_n|$</li><li>$e^{\hat{Q}}\equiv1+\hat{Q}+\frac{1}{2}\hat{Q}^2+\frac{1}{3!}\hat{Q}^3+…$</li><li>$\frac{1}{1-\hat{Q}}\equiv1+\hat{Q}+\hat{Q}^2+\hat{Q}^3+\hat{Q}^4+…$</li><li>$ln(1+\hat{Q})\equiv\hat{Q}-\frac{1}{2}\hat{Q}^2+\frac{1}{3}\hat{Q}^3-\frac{1}{4}\hat{Q}^4+…$</li></ul></li><li>Changing Bases In Dirac Notation<ul><li>利用恒等算符方便换基底</li></ul></li></ul></li></ul></li></ul><h2 id="希尔伯特空间、内积、算符、基矢、系数">希尔伯特空间、内积、算符、基矢、系数</h2>]]></content>
      
      
